<article>

  <p>
    Most of a day is spent arranging conditions — work, food, company, the next
    small relief — as if the right arrangement would finally let the mind rest.
    Sometimes the arrangement works for a stretch. The meal lands; the errand
    is done; nobody is angry. And still something fails to settle. Pleasant
    moments thin out. Anticipation turns into surplus. Relief becomes the next
    wanting. The oscillation is ordinary enough that it rarely gets named as a
    problem of the first order.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Dhammacakkappavattana
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span>
    (SN 56.11) begins there. Not with cosmology, gods, or the fate of the self
    after death — with
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>,
    the unsatisfactoriness threaded through conditioned experience. The title
    means something like "the discourse that sets the wheel of the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="teaching">Dhamma</span>
    in motion." What turns is not a creed handed down from outside. It is a
    relationship to experience that can be tested.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Nothing to Believe First</h2>

  <p>
    A common reading of "first teaching" treats the text as the opening chapter
    of a religion: accept these propositions, then practice. That order is
    backwards for how the discourse actually moves. The Buddha walks to the Deer
    Park at Isipatana to find five
    <span class="pali" data-pali="bhikkhu" data-en="ones on the path">bhikkhus</span>
    who had left him when he abandoned extreme austerity. They already knew life
    had a problem. They had already left the household to solve it. What they
    lacked was not intensity. It was a workable diagnosis.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sutta does not ask them — or a later reader — to install a metaphysics
    package before looking. It asks whether
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
    can be recognised as it is, whether its cause can be seen, whether cessation
    is conceivable, and whether a trainable path follows from that seeing. Faith
    in rebirth, heavens, or the architecture of the cosmos is not the entrance
    exam. Those questions appear elsewhere in the canon, and often by careful
    refusal rather than theory. Here the entrance is simpler and harder: look at
    wanting and not-wanting without flinching.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course the tradition holds larger claims — including craving that leads to
    renewed existence. Whether those claims are ultimately true or not, living
    <em>as if</em> intentional thirst has consequences still changes what one is
    willing to chase, clutch, or harm. That change improves this life either way.
    The first discourse, though, does not wait on the cosmology to land. It starts
    with what is already available in ordinary attention.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Two Ways of Fighting Experience</h2>

  <p>
    Before the four truths, the Buddha draws a practical cut. Two extremes are
    not for someone who has gone forth: devotion to sensual pleasure, and
    devotion to self-mortification. Both are unprofitable. Between them is the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="majjhimā-paṭipadā" data-en="middle way">majjhimā paṭipadā</span>
    — the middle way — which the discourse identifies with the
    <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>.
    The
    <a href="/concepts/middle-way/">Middle Way page</a>
    unpacks that cut: what each extreme is doing, why "balance" is too thin a
    reading, and how the refusal shows up in early ethics and sitting. Here the
    cut clears the ground so the four truths can be heard as tasks.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Four Truths as Four Tasks</h2>

  <p>
    The core of the discourse is the four noble truths, spoken in the language of
    a physician: condition, cause, ending, cure. They are not four slogans to
    recite after dinner. They are four tasks — each with a different demand on
    attention.
  </p>

  <h3>Dukkha — to be fully understood</h3>

  <p>
    Birth, aging, illness, and death are
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>;
    so are association with what one dislikes, separation from what one loves, and
    not getting what one wants. In brief: the five aggregates subject to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="upadāna" data-en="clinging">upadāna</span>
    — clinging — are
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is not the claim that life is uniformly miserable. Joy is real. So is the
    way joy fails to stay. The teaching names a pervasive unsatisfactoriness in
    conditioned things — including the subtle friction of change — without denying
    pleasure. Pessimism is a misreading. Diagnosis is not. The first task is not
    to brood about suffering. It is to understand it thoroughly enough that the
    mind stops mistaking rearrangement for liberation.
  </p>

  <h3>Tanhā — to be abandoned</h3>

  <p>
    The origin of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
    is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="tanhā" data-en="craving">tanhā</span>
    — craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and passion,
    seeking delight here and there: craving for sensual pleasure, craving for
    existence, craving for extermination.     The problem is not that objects exist.
    The problem is the thirst that keeps leaning toward and away from them —
    chasing what delights, pushing off what displeases, and missing the moment
    in which that lean can be known.
  </p>

  <h3>Nibbāna — to be realised</h3>

  <p>
    The cessation of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
    is the remainderless fading and cessation of that same craving — its
    abandonment and relinquishment. This is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation">nibbāna</span>:
    not the annihilation of a person, but the extinguishing of the fire that drives
    continued becoming. What goes out is the fuel. The texts are deliberately
    careful about what remains when the fuel is gone — notes, not a closed picture.
  </p>

  <h3>The path — to be developed</h3>

  <p>
    The path leading to that cessation is the
    <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>.
    The prescription follows from the diagnosis. No separate metaphysics is
    required to begin developing view, intention, speech, action, livelihood,
    effort, mindfulness, and unification as one work rather than eight upgrades.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "This is the noble truth of suffering… This noble truth of suffering is to be fully
    understood… This noble truth of suffering has been fully understood."
    <cite>— SN 56.11 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <hr>

  <h2>Twelve Aspects, Not Twelve Slogans</h2>

  <p>
    Easy to skim past, costly to miss: for each truth the Buddha describes three
    "turnings" of the wheel — the statement of the truth; what must be done with
    respect to it; and the confirmation that it has been done. Four truths, three
    aspects each: twelve facets of one seeing.
  </p>

  <p>
    For
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>:
    <em>this is dukkha</em> —
    <em>dukkha is to be fully understood</em> —
    <em>dukkha has been fully understood</em>.
    For the origin: this is the origin; it is to be abandoned; it has been
    abandoned. For cessation: this is cessation; it is to be realised; it has been
    realised. For the path: this is the path; it is to be developed; it has been
    developed.
  </p>

  <p>
    The structure makes the teaching empirical rather than merely doctrinal. These
    are not propositions parked in the intellect. They describe a relationship
    between attention and experience that can be tested in principle — and that,
    on the far side of the work, can be confirmed. The third turning is not
    something a first-time listener can honestly claim. It is what the Buddha
    reports from completed knowing. It functions as both credential and promise:
    this can be known directly, because it has been.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course a report is not yet one's own seeing. The sutta does not collapse
    that gap. It names it — and leaves the middle turning as the reader's actual
    work.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Kondañña Understood</h2>

  <p>
    At the end of the discourse, one of the five — Kondañña — attains the first
    stage of awakening. The text records that there arose in him the dustless,
    stainless vision of the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="teaching">Dhamma</span>:
    "Whatever is subject to origination is all subject to cessation."
  </p>

  <p>
    The seeing is precise. Not "everything changes" as a vague mood, but the
    specific recognition that anything arisen through conditions will cease when
    those conditions cease. That is the turn. If craving is a condition, and
    craving can cease, then the suffering that depends on it is not a permanent
    feature of being alive. Kondañña has understood on what liberation turns.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Buddha responds:
    <em>"Kondañña has understood! Kondañña has understood!"</em>
    — and from this he receives the name Aññāsi Kondañña: Kondañña-who-has-known.
    The wheel is no longer only what one person has seen alone. It is something
    that can be transmitted, practiced, and confirmed in another mind.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What the Wheel Asks</h2>

  <p>
    In a sense, this sutta is the frame within which much of the rest of the
    canon operates. The four truths are the diagnostic structure the tradition
    returns to again and again. Reading it carefully means noticing what it
    declines to settle as much as what it affirms.
  </p>

  <p>
    It does not say that life is a mistake. It does not finish the metaphysics of
    self and afterlife in this first talk — those questions arrive later, and
    often by refusal rather than theory. It says there is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>,
    that it has a cause that can be understood, that cessation is possible, and
    that there is a trainable path. Notes, not a closed system.
  </p>

  <p>
    The question it puts to a reader is not "Do you accept these four
    propositions?" It is closer to: are you willing to look at wanting and
    not-wanting honestly enough to see whether the diagnosis holds? The rest of
    the canon elaborates. This text turns the wheel.
  </p>

</article>
